<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
My Woodelf Zombie Archer has the following Junkart effects...<br>
 <br>
 Activate for Satisfy Hunger<br>
 Activate for Cure Insanity<br>
 Activate for Cure cuts<br>
 Activate for Teleport Level<br>
 Activate for Genocide every 500 turns<br>
 Activate for Remove Fear and Cure poison every 5 turns<br>
 Activate for Aquirement<br>
 Activate for Curing<br>
 Activate for Cure Fear<br>
 Activate for Summon Monster<br>
 <br>
 Mathomed-<br>
 Activate for Decreasing Constitution<br>
 Activate for Blindness<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 A few questions<br>
 Does curing cover cuts, and is the Aquirement affected by DL?<br>
 Found in the last Half Hour<br>
 Activate for High Experience Loss<br>
 Activate for Corruption [could be usefull if i get bored :-P] <br>
 Activate for creat hunger<br>
 <p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Ah, another wood-elf player.... :D 
</p>
<p>
Keep the Satisfy Hunger, Geno, and Teleport level ones by all means, plus, depending on your class, the Cure Insanity one. An archer really doesn't need cure fear, but the fear/poison one might be useful until you get rpoison. The Curing one...maybe, for last ditch help. (For junkart life-saving purposes, I personally prefer the cure 700 hp one if I can find it, which I usually do.) Summon monster is handy for Beastmaster quests or knocking off critters to create totems, but you can generally find a wand of the same, which is a lot more convenient.  
</p>
<p>
If you ever find a Light Absorption junkart, hang on to it! 
</p>
<p>
Acquirement junkarts are fun to play with, but they rarely produce truly great items and have a looong recharge time. They are affected by DL as far as I know. But even then, they're not all THAT great. Best I ever got out of one on the top level of Angband was a ROS +6 or +7; aside from that it was all Foo of Resist Lightning or whatever. I have, however, heard of people getting artifacts off them. After literally hours spent scumming, though, I never managed it myself. 
</p>
<p>
I'm fairly certain that curing covers cuts, but check first (I'm way tired.) However, if you are walking into shards attacks, you should be carrying a big pile of Cure Critical Wounds potions rather than a Cure Cuts junkart, because a single junkart takes a long time to recharge and repeated shards attacks can wreck your whole day. 
</p>
<p>
My current char has two copies of Kelek's Wormhole Machine, which in her case happens to activate for geno...yay :-) (plus, iirc, another junk by another name which activates for the same thing....) 
</p>
<p>
It's weird, but some DLs just seem to be junkart magnets. I have one character who has a specific dungeon town in which, during revisits, I've never found less than 3 junkarts.  
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: Keep the Curing Junkart, since it cures blindness, poison, confusion, stun, cuts and hallucination. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./TobiasParker">TobiasParker</a></strong>:I have about 15 of these stupid things.  Right now i am keeping the Geno, Tel Level, Curing, Aquirement, The cure insanity and the satisy hunger, i decided to pump up magic device and so now they all activate on a consistant basis...almost died to hunger after failing for about 1000 turns.  This char is probably my best ever but he is horribly equipped i am missing like 6 resists so i am keeping every possible life saver around. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: With my actual <a class="interwiki" title="Self" href="./MassimilianoMarangio/Eonwe">character</a>, I found 74 of the junkarts, mathomed 62 and use most of the remaining 12 :-) 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./TobiasParker">TobiasParker</a></strong>: Died...as usual.  Stupid gondolin troll quest.  I have lost 2 of my last 4 characters to it. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./ErisDiscordia">ErisDiscordia</a></strong>: You never know with Acquirement junkarts, though. I have one with a current character, and though it usually produces the usual vaguely-valuable-but-useless poop, it once (in Erebor) acquired Elessar. If you ever get it again: if you're short for house space or inventory space (it's useless if you can't carry it when diving), dump it. Otherwise, give it a whirl at the end of each dive. Well, it also depends on how much you tend to travel the wilderness -- each turn of wilderness travel counts as a large number of ordinary turns, so such a junkart will generally be recharged by the time you go from one town to another (e.g. for housekeeping). This is the only way to recharge the durn thing reasonably fast without scumming, so if you don't travel much, definitely drop it. 
</p>
